      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Patient's Demands Versus a Doctor's Convictions'' (Essay, April 3): I do not agree with Dr. Sandeep Jauhar's essay. It's one thing to give patients a choice of several acceptable alternatives. But ultimately, the doctor needs to use his or her objective and educated judgment about what is acceptable.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Patient's Demands Versus a Doctor's Convictions'' (Essay, April 3): I do not agree with Dr. Sandeep Jauhar's essay. It's one thing to give patients a choice of several acceptable alternatives. But ultimately, the doctor needs to use his or her objective and educated judgment about what is acceptable.</p>
        <p>Doctors shouldn't be treating themselves or their loved ones. Certainly, then, we shouldn't be letting the average patient tell their doctor to treat them in a way that the doctor feels is inappropriate. The patient can get a second (or third or fourth) opinion if they wish.</p>
        <p>Elizabeth Korn  Basking Ridge, N.J.</p>
      </block>
